    "body": "## Summary\n\n`cmux browser --help` lists `screencast`, `network requests/route/unroute`, and `trace start/stop` as available subcommands. At runtime, the engine returns `not_supported: browser.X is not supported on WKWebView` for each. Help should reflect actual capability.\n\n## Reproduction\n\n```bash\ncmux browser open https://example.com   # works\n\ncmux browser --surface surface:N screencast start\n# Error: not_supported: browser.screencast.start is not supported on WKWebView\n\ncmux browser --surface surface:N trace start /tmp/x.zip\n# Error: not_supported: browser.trace.start is not supported on WKWebView\n\ncmux browser --surface surface:N network requests\n# Error: not_supported: browser.network.requests is not supported on WKWebView\n```\n\n## Why this matters\n\nThese verbs are listed unconditionally in `cmux browser --help`. Users (and AI agents reading help) can't tell from the output that they're Chromium-only. I had a deploy-verification recipe documented around `cmux browser screencast start` for months before discovering it had never worked silently — `screencast` was in help, the call errored, the recipe had no error handling.\n\n## Suggested fix\n\nPick whichever is least invasive:\n\n1. **Annotate** unsupported verbs in `--help` with `(Chromium-only — not on WKWebView)`\n2. **Filter** them out of `--help` when `--surface` resolves to a WKWebView surface\n3. **Document** the WKWebView vs Chromium support matrix in README/docs\n\nOption 3 alone would have caught it.\n\n## Environment\n\n- cmux 0.63.2 stable\n- macOS 25.4.0 (Darwin)\n- WKWebView (Apple WebKit, verified via `otool -L /Applications/cmux.app/Contents/MacOS/cmux`)",
